  "notes": [
    "Spanish stress is deterministic from orthography: words ending in vowel/n/s default to penultimate stress; words ending in any other consonant take ultimate stress; written accent marks override both rules.",
    "Stress is rendered by uppercasing the entire stressed syllable in the respelling output (e.g. ka-FE for café).",
    "Latin American Spanish is assumed: no Castilian /θ/ (cz/zc/c-before-i-or-e all map to /s/). Argentine /ʃ/ for ll/y is noted on dialect-marked entries but the default ll mapping is 'ly' for v1 clarity to a US English reader.",
    "Single-tap r (ɾ) vs trilled rr (r) is preserved as a phonemic distinction. English speakers tend to collapse both; the similarity matrix penalizes the collapse softly.",
    "Intervocalic b/d/g become approximants (β/ð/ɣ). Speakers don't need to produce the approximant cleanly to be understood; the respelling renders them as their stop counterparts (b/d/g) for English readability.",
    "v is pronounced identically to b in Spanish; the table maps via IPA only.",
    "h is silent in Spanish; words spelled with h have no entry — the IPA simply omits it.",
    "Diphthongs are rendered as the closest US English digraph; some (eu, iu) have no clean English analogue and use the closest sequence."
  ],
  "entries": [
