    { "ipa": "ʎ", "respelling": "ly", "notes": "palatal lateral; written ll. Default 'ly' (calle → KAH-lyeh). Dialect variants: most Latin American merges to /ʝ/ ~ 'y' (yeísmo); Argentine/Uruguayan uses /ʃ/ ~ 'sh' (sheísmo). v1 picks 'ly' as the most pronunciation-distinct option for an English reader." },
    { "ipa": "ʝ", "respelling": "y", "notes": "palatal fricative/approximant; written y intervocalic or ll in yeísta dialects (mayo → MAH-yoh)" },
    { "ipa": "r", "respelling": "rr", "notes": "alveolar trill; multi-tap. Written rr, or single r word-initial / after n,l,s. Mark as 'rr' to remind learner it's trilled (perro → PEH-rroh)" },
    { "ipa": "ɾ", "respelling": "r", "notes": "alveolar tap; single flap. Written single r between vowels or in clusters. Like the 'tt' in American English 'butter' (pero → PEH-roh)" },
    { "ipa": "s", "respelling": "s", "notes": "voiceless alveolar fricative; consistent across Latin America (no Castilian /θ/)" },
